# DDD: No Primitive Obsession

This rule enforces Domain-Driven Design best practices by **REQUIRING** all primitive values to be wrapped in Value Objects, Entities, or Aggregates. This prevents the "primitive obsession" anti-pattern and ensures domain concepts are properly encapsulated with their business rules.

## Core Principle: Primitives Must Be Wrapped

**MUST NOT** use primitive types (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, `Date`) directly for domain concepts across all DDD layers.

**MUST** wrap all domain concepts in Value Objects, Entities, or Aggregates.

**Applies to:**
- Domain layer (`packages/**/domain/`, `apps/**/domain/`)
- Application layer (`packages/**/application/`, `apps/**/application/`)
- Infrastructure layer (`apps/**/infrastructure/`)

## Rationale

- **Type safety**: Compiler catches domain rule violations at compile time
- **Encapsulation**: Business rules and validation live with the data they protect
- **Validation**: Single place to enforce constraints and invariants
- **Expressiveness**: `Title` is clearer and more meaningful than `string`
- **Refactoring safety**: Changes to business rules are localized to Value Objects
- **Self-documenting**: Code communicates domain concepts explicitly
- **Prevents invalid states**: Value Objects cannot be created in invalid states

## Mandatory Patterns

### Property Declarations

Domain object properties **MUST** use Value Objects, never primitives.

#### ✅ CORRECT - Wrapped in Value Objects

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/entities/event.ts
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,                      // ✅ Value Object for ID
    private readonly title: Title,                 // ✅ Value Object for title
    private readonly description: Description,     // ✅ Value Object for description
    private readonly startDate: StartDate,         // ✅ Value Object for date
    private readonly price: Price,                 // ✅ Value Object for price
    private readonly venueName: VenueName,         // ✅ Value Object for venue
    private readonly cityName: CityName,           // ✅ Value Object for city
    private readonly source: Source,               // ✅ Value Object for enum
  ) {}
  
  getId(): Id {
    return this.id
  }
  
  getTitle(): Title {
    return this.title
  }
  
  getPrice(): Price {
    return this.price
  }
}
```

#### ❌ INCORRECT - Primitive Obsession

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Using primitives directly
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: string,          // ❌ Should be Id value object
    private readonly title: string,       // ❌ Should be Title value object
    private readonly description: string, // ❌ Should be Description value object
    private readonly startDate: Date,     // ❌ Should be StartDate value object
    private readonly price: number,       // ❌ Should be Price value object
    private readonly venueName: string,   // ❌ Should be VenueName value object
  ) {}
  
  // ❌ WRONG - Returning primitives
  getTitle(): string {
    return this.title
  }
  
  getPrice(): number {
    return this.price
  }
}
```

### Method Signatures

Public method parameters and return types **MUST** use Value Objects, Entities, or Aggregates.

#### ✅ CORRECT - Value Objects in Public API

```typescript
// packages/events/application/use-cases/create-event-admin.use-case.ts
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventAdminUseCase {
  async execute(
    title: Title,                    // ✅ Value Object parameter
    description: Description,        // ✅ Value Object parameter
    startDate: StartDate,           // ✅ Value Object parameter
    cityId: CityId,                 // ✅ Value Object parameter
    categoryIds: CategoryId[],      // ✅ Array of Value Objects
    price: Price,                   // ✅ Value Object parameter
  ): Promise<Event> {               // ✅ Returns Entity
    // Implementation
  }
}

// packages/events/domain/entities/event.ts
export class Event {
  calculateDuration(): EventDurationTier {  // ✅ Returns Value Object
    // Business logic
  }
  
  isInCity(cityName: CityName): boolean {   // ✅ Parameter is Value Object
    return this.cityName.equals(cityName)
  }
  
  changePrice(newPrice: Price): void {      // ✅ Parameter is Value Object
    // Validation and business rules
  }
}
```

#### ❌ INCORRECT - Primitives in Public API

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Primitives in use case
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventAdminUseCase {
  async execute(
    title: string,              // ❌ Should be Title value object
    description: string,        // ❌ Should be Description value object
    startDate: Date,           // ❌ Should be StartDate value object
    cityId: string,            // ❌ Should be CityId value object
    price: number,             // ❌ Should be Price value object
  ): Promise<Event> {
    // ❌ No validation, no business rules
  }
}

// ❌ WRONG - Primitives in domain methods
export class Event {
  calculateDuration(): number {  // ❌ Should return EventDurationTier
    return 120
  }
  
  isInCity(cityName: string): boolean {  // ❌ Should be CityName
    return this.cityName === cityName
  }
  
  changePrice(newPrice: number): void {  // ❌ Should be Price
    this.price = newPrice  // ❌ No validation!
  }
}
```

### Repository Methods

Repository method signatures **MUST** use Value Objects for IDs and domain concepts.

#### ✅ CORRECT - Value Objects in Repository

```typescript
// packages/events/infrastructure/persistence/prisma/event.repository.ts
@Injectable()
export class EventPrismaRepository {
  async findById(id: EventId): Promise<Event | null> {  // ✅ Value Object parameter
    const row = await this.prisma.event.findUnique({
      where: { id: id.toString() }  // ✅ Convert to primitive for Prisma
    })
    return row ? Event.fromDto(row) : null
  }
  
  async findByCityAndDateRange(
    cityId: CityId,           // ✅ Value Object
    startDate: StartDate,     // ✅ Value Object
    endDate: EndDate,         // ✅ Value Object
  ): Promise<Event[]> {
    // Implementation
  }
  
  async save(event: Event): Promise<Event> {  // ✅ Entity parameter and return
    // Implementation
  }
}
```

#### ❌ INCORRECT - Primitives in Repository

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Primitives in repository
@Injectable()
export class EventPrismaRepository {
  async findById(id: string): Promise<Event | null> {  // ❌ Should be EventId
    // No validation on ID format
  }
  
  async findByCityAndDateRange(
    cityId: string,      // ❌ Should be CityId
    startDate: Date,     // ❌ Should be StartDate
    endDate: Date,       // ❌ Should be EndDate
  ): Promise<Event[]> {
    // No validation on dates or city
  }
}
```

## Allowed Exceptions

### Exception 1: DTOs and Transfer Objects

DTOs (Data Transfer Objects) used for serialization, database mapping, and API responses **MAY** use primitives. This is the primary exception to the rule.

#### ✅ ALLOWED - Primitives in DTOs

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/dtos/event.dto.ts
// ✅ ALLOWED - DTO for serialization
export interface EventDto {
  id: string                // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from Id
  title: string             // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from Title
  slug: string              // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from Slug
  description: string       // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from Description
  startDate: Date           // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from StartDate
  endDate: Date             // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from EndDate
  price: string             // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from Price
  venueName: string         // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from VenueName
  categoryIds: string[]     // ✅ Primitive OK - serialized from CategoryId[]
  isVerified: boolean       // ✅ Primitive OK - simple flag
}

// ✅ ALLOWED - Database DTO
export interface EventDatabaseDto {
  id: string
  title: string
  slug: string
  // ... all primitives OK for database mapping
}

// ✅ ALLOWED - API response DTO
export interface EventFrontendDto {
  id: string
  title: string
  // ... primitives OK for API serialization
}
```

#### ✅ ALLOWED - Transformation to/from DTOs

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/entities/event.ts
export class Event {
  // ✅ ALLOWED - toDto() returns DTO with primitives
  toDto(): EventDto {
    return {
      id: this.id.toString(),               // ✅ Convert Value Object to primitive
      title: this.title.toString(),         // ✅ Convert Value Object to primitive
      description: this.description.toString(),
      startDate: this.startDate.toDate(),   // ✅ Convert Value Object to Date
      price: this.price.toString(),         // ✅ Convert Value Object to string
      venueName: this.venueName.toString(),
      categoryIds: this.categories.map(c => c.getId().toString()),
      isVerified: this.isVerified,
    }
  }
  
  // ✅ ALLOWED - fromDto() accepts DTO with primitives
  static fromDto(dto: EventDatabaseDto): Event {
    return new Event(
      Id.createFrom(dto.id),                    // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      Title.create(dto.title),                  // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      Description.create(dto.description),      // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      StartDate.create(dto.startDate),         // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      Price.createFromString(dto.price),       // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      VenueName.create(dto.venueName),         // ✅ Create Value Object from primitive
      // ...
    )
  }
}
```

### Exception 2: Internal Private Implementation

Value Objects **MAY** use private primitives internally after validation.

#### ✅ ALLOWED - Private Primitive After Validation

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/title.ts
export class Title {
  // ✅ ALLOWED - Private primitive after validation
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}
  
  static create(input: string): Title {
    // Validation here ensures value is always valid
    if (!input || input.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Title cannot be empty', 400)
    }
    if (input.length > 200) {
      throw new OneJsError('Title too long', 400)
    }
    return new Title(input.trim())
  }
  
  // ✅ ALLOWED - Return primitive for external use
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }
  
  getValue(): string {
    return this.value
  }
  
  equals(other: Title): boolean {
    return this.value === other.value
  }
}
```

### Exception 3: Infrastructure Layer Data Mapping

Infrastructure code that interfaces with external systems (Prisma, APIs, S3) **MAY** use primitives for data mapping.

#### ✅ ALLOWED - Database Queries with Primitives

```typescript
// packages/events/infrastructure/persistence/prisma/event.repository.ts
@Injectable()
export class EventPrismaRepository {
  async findById(id: EventId): Promise<Event | null> {
    // ✅ ALLOWED - Prisma needs primitive string
    const row = await this.prisma.event.findUnique({
      where: { id: id.toString() }  // ✅ Convert to primitive for Prisma
    })
    
    if (!row) return null
    
    // ✅ Convert back to domain objects
    return Event.fromDto(row)
  }
  
  async save(event: Event): Promise<Event> {
    // ✅ ALLOWED - Convert to primitives for database
    const dto = event.toDto()
    
    const saved = await this.prisma.event.upsert({
      where: { id: dto.id },  // ✅ Primitive for Prisma
      update: dto,
      create: dto,
    })
    
    // ✅ Convert back to domain entity
    return Event.fromDto(saved)
  }
}
```

#### ✅ ALLOWED - External API Calls

```typescript
// apps/scheduler/src/infrastructure/openai/openai.client.ts
@Injectable()
export class OpenAIClient {
  async extractEvents(imageUrl: string): Promise<ExtractedEvent[]> {
    // ✅ ALLOWED - External API needs primitives
    const response = await openai.chat.completions.create({
      model: 'gpt-4',
      messages: [
        {
          type: 'text',
          text: 'Extract events from image',  // ✅ Primitive for API
        },
        {
          type: 'image_url',
          image_url: { url: imageUrl },  // ✅ Primitive for API
        },
      ],
    })
    
    // ✅ Parse and convert to domain objects
    const extracted = JSON.parse(response.choices[0].message.content)
    return extracted.map(e => ({
      title: Title.create(e.title),        // ✅ Convert to Value Objects
      startDate: StartDate.create(e.date),
      venue: VenueName.create(e.venue),
    }))
  }
}
```

### Exception 4: Simple Utility Functions

Pure utility functions with clear mathematical or computational purpose **MAY** use primitives.

#### ✅ ALLOWED - Math and Utility Functions

```typescript
// utils/date-helpers.ts
// ✅ ALLOWED - Simple utility, not domain logic
export function calculateDaysBetween(date1: Date, date2: Date): number {
  const diffMs = Math.abs(date2.getTime() - date1.getTime())
  return Math.floor(diffMs / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24))
}

// ✅ ALLOWED - Pure computation
export function calculatePercentage(part: number, total: number): number {
  if (total === 0) return 0
  return (part / total) * 100
}

// ✅ ALLOWED - String manipulation utility
export function slugify(text: string): string {
  return text
    .toLowerCase()
    .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, '-')
    .replace(/(^-|-$)/g, '')
}
```

#### ❌ INCORRECT - Domain Logic with Primitives

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Domain logic should use Value Objects
export function calculateEventPrice(
  basePrice: number,        // ❌ Should be Price value object
  discount: number,         // ❌ Should be Discount value object
): number {                 // ❌ Should return Price value object
  // Business rules without validation
  return basePrice * (1 - discount)
}

// ✅ CORRECT - Domain service with Value Objects
@Injectable()
export class EventPricingService {
  calculateDiscountedPrice(
    basePrice: Price,         // ✅ Value Object
    discount: DiscountRate,   // ✅ Value Object
  ): Price {                  // ✅ Returns Value Object
    // Business rules with validation
    return basePrice.applyDiscount(discount)
  }
}
```

## Exception Documentation Format

When using primitives in allowed contexts, document the exception:

```typescript
// EXCEPTION: Primitive allowed - DTO for API serialization
export interface EventPublicDto {
  id: string          // Converted from Id value object
  title: string       // Converted from Title value object
  price: string       // Converted from Price value object
}

// EXCEPTION: Primitive allowed - Prisma database query
const events = await this.prisma.event.findMany({
  where: { cityId: cityId.toString() }  // Prisma requires string
})

// EXCEPTION: Primitive allowed - OpenAI API request
const response = await openai.chat.completions.create({
  messages: [{ role: 'user', content: prompt }]  // API requires string
})
```

## Common Value Objects to Create

Reference existing patterns from the codebase:

### Identifiers

Create Value Objects for all entity IDs:

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/id.ts
export class Id {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}
  
  static generate(): Id {
    return new Id(crypto.randomUUID())
  }
  
  static createFrom(value: string): Id {
    if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('ID cannot be empty', 400)
    }
    return new Id(value)
  }
  
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }
  
  equals(other: Id): boolean {
    return this.value === other.value
  }
}
```

**Common ID Value Objects:**
- `Id` / `EventId` / `CategoryId` / `CityId` / `TagId`
- `EventImageId`
- `ExternalId` (for external system IDs)

### Text Values

Create Value Objects for all text fields with business rules:

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/title.ts
export class Title {
  private static readonly MAX_LENGTH = 200
  
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}
  
  static create(input: string): Title {
    if (!input || input.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Title cannot be empty',
        400,
        'Title is required for events',
        undefined,
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }
    
    const trimmed = input.trim()
    
    if (trimmed.length > this.MAX_LENGTH) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Title too long',
        400,
        `Title must not exceed ${this.MAX_LENGTH} characters`,
        { length: trimmed.length, max: this.MAX_LENGTH },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }
    
    return new Title(trimmed)
  }
  
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }
}
```

**Common Text Value Objects:**
- `Title`, `Description`, `LongDescription`
- `VenueName`, `VenueAddress`
- `CityName`, `CategoryName`, `TagName`
- `Username`, `Email`
- `Slug`, `ShortCode`

### Dates and Times

Create Value Objects for all date/time values with validation:

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/start-date.ts
export class StartDate {
  private constructor(private readonly value: Date) {}
  
  static create(input: Date | string | number): StartDate {
    let date: Date
    
    if (input instanceof Date) {
      date = input
    } else if (typeof input === 'string' || typeof input === 'number') {
      date = new Date(input)
    } else {
      throw new OneJsError('Invalid date format', 400)
    }
    
    if (Number.isNaN(date.getTime())) {
      throw new OneJsError('Invalid date', 400)
    }
    
    return new StartDate(date)
  }
  
  toDate(): Date {
    return new Date(this.value)
  }
  
  isBefore(other: StartDate): boolean {
    return this.value < other.value
  }
  
  isAfter(other: StartDate): boolean {
    return this.value > other.value
  }
}
```

**Common Date/Time Value Objects:**
- `StartDate`, `EndDate`
- `StartTime`, `EndTime`, `DisplayTime`
- `CreatedAt`, `UpdatedAt`

### Money and Prices

Create Value Objects for monetary values:

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/price.ts
export class Price {
  private constructor(
    private readonly amount: number,
    private readonly currency: string,
  ) {}
  
  static create(amount: number, currency = 'USD'): Price {
    if (amount < 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Price cannot be negative', 400)
    }
    if (!Number.isFinite(amount)) {
      throw new OneJsError('Price must be a valid number', 400)
    }
    return new Price(amount, currency)
  }
  
  static free(): Price {
    return new Price(0, 'USD')
  }
  
  static createFromString(input: string): Price | null {
    if (!input || input.toLowerCase() === 'free') {
      return Price.free()
    }
    
    const amount = Number.parseFloat(input)
    if (Number.isNaN(amount)) {
      return null
    }
    
    return Price.create(amount)
  }
  
  toString(): string {
    return this.amount === 0 ? 'Free' : `$${this.amount.toFixed(2)}`
  }
  
  getValue(): number {
    return this.amount
  }
}
```

### Enumerations

Create Value Objects for domain enums:

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/source.ts
export enum SourceEnum {
  INSTAGRAM = 'instagram',
  MANUAL = 'manual',
  API = 'api',
}

export class Source {
  private constructor(private readonly value: SourceEnum) {}
  
  static create(input: SourceEnum | string): Source {
    const normalized = input.toLowerCase()
    
    if (!Object.values(SourceEnum).includes(normalized as SourceEnum)) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Invalid source',
        400,
        `Source must be one of: ${Object.values(SourceEnum).join(', ')}`,
        { input },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }
    
    return new Source(normalized as SourceEnum)
  }
  
  isInstagram(): boolean {
    return this.value === SourceEnum.INSTAGRAM
  }
  
  isManual(): boolean {
    return this.value === SourceEnum.MANUAL
  }
  
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }
  
  equals(other: Source): boolean {
    return this.value === other.value
  }
}
```

**Common Enum Value Objects:**
- `Source`, `DayPeriod`, `EventDurationTier`
- `UserRole`, `EventStatus`
- `CategoryType`

## Benefits of Value Objects

### Type Safety

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Primitives allow mistakes
function createEvent(
  title: string,
  cityId: string,
  categoryId: string,
) {
  // Easy to mix up parameters!
  repository.save(title, categoryId, cityId)  // ❌ Wrong order, compiles fine
}

// ✅ GOOD - Value Objects catch mistakes at compile time
function createEvent(
  title: Title,
  cityId: CityId,
  categoryId: CategoryId,
) {
  // ✅ Type system prevents mistakes
  repository.save(title, categoryId, cityId)  // ❌ Compile error - wrong types!
  repository.save(title, cityId, categoryId)  // ✅ Correct order enforced
}
```

### Validation at Boundaries

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Validation scattered everywhere
function createEvent(title: string) {
  if (!title || title.trim().length === 0) {  // Validation here
    throw new Error('Invalid title')
  }
  // ... more code
}

function updateEvent(title: string) {
  if (!title || title.trim().length === 0) {  // Duplicated validation
    throw new Error('Invalid title')
  }
  // ... more code
}

// ✅ GOOD - Validation in one place
function createEvent(title: Title) {
  // No validation needed - Title is always valid
}

function updateEvent(title: Title) {
  // No validation needed - Title is always valid
}

// Validation happens at creation:
const title = Title.create(userInput)  // ✅ Single validation point
```

### Self-Documenting Code

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - What do these numbers mean?
function calculateScore(
  value1: number,
  value2: number,
  value3: number,
): number {
  return value1 * value2 + value3
}

// ✅ GOOD - Clear business meaning
function calculateEventPopularityScore(
  attendeeCount: AttendeeCount,
  averageRating: AverageRating,
  recencyBonus: RecencyBonus,
): PopularityScore {
  return PopularityScore.calculate(attendeeCount, averageRating, recencyBonus)
}
```

### Business Rules Encapsulation

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Business rules scattered in application layer
@Injectable()
export class EventService {
  createEvent(price: number) {
    if (price < 0) throw new Error('Price cannot be negative')
    if (price > 10000) throw new Error('Price too high')
    // Business rules in application layer
  }
  
  updateEvent(price: number) {
    if (price < 0) throw new Error('Price cannot be negative')
    if (price > 10000) throw new Error('Price too high')
    // Duplicated business rules
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD - Business rules in Value Object
export class Price {
  private static readonly MAX_PRICE = 10000
  
  static create(amount: number): Price {
    if (amount < 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Price cannot be negative', 400)
    }
    if (amount > this.MAX_PRICE) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Price exceeds maximum allowed',
        400,
        `Maximum price is ${this.MAX_PRICE}`,
      )
    }
    return new Price(amount)
  }
}

@Injectable()
export class EventService {
  createEvent(price: Price) {
    // ✅ No validation - Price is always valid
  }
  
  updateEvent(price: Price) {
    // ✅ No validation - Price is always valid
  }
}
```

## Migration Strategy

When introducing Value Objects to existing code with primitives:

### Step 1: Create Value Object

```typescript
// Create new Value Object
export class EventTitle {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}
  
  static create(input: string): EventTitle {
    // Add validation
    return new EventTitle(input)
  }
  
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }
}
```

### Step 2: Update Domain Layer

```typescript
// Update entity to use Value Object
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly title: EventTitle,  // Changed from string
    // ...
  ) {}
  
  getTitle(): EventTitle {  // Changed from string
    return this.title
  }
}
```

### Step 3: Update Application Layer

```typescript
// Update use cases
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventUseCase {
  async execute(
    title: EventTitle,  // Changed from string
    // ...
  ): Promise<Event> {
    // Implementation
  }
}
```

### Step 4: Update Transformation Points

```typescript
// Update controllers to create Value Objects
@Controller('/events')
export class EventsController {
  @Post('/')
  async createEvent(ctx: Context) {
    const { title } = ctx.body
    
    // Create Value Object from user input
    const titleVO = EventTitle.create(title)
    
    const event = await this.createEventUseCase.execute(titleVO)
    return event.toDto()
  }
}
```

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- Wrap all domain concepts in Value Objects
- Use Value Objects for IDs, text, dates, money, enums
- Create Value Objects with validation in `static create()` methods
- Use private constructors in Value Objects
- Return Value Objects from domain methods
- Accept Value Objects as method parameters
- Use DTOs with primitives for serialization
- Convert between Value Objects and primitives at boundaries
- Document exceptions when using primitives

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't use primitives for domain concepts in entities
- Don't use primitives in use case parameters
- Don't use primitives in domain method signatures
- Don't scatter validation logic across application layer
- Don't skip Value Objects "for convenience"
- Don't expose primitives in public domain APIs
- Don't create Value Objects without validation
- Don't use public constructors in Value Objects

